#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:4
msgid "F2PY examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:6
msgid ""
"Below are some examples of F2PY usage. This list is not comprehensive, but "
"can be used as a starting point when wrapping your own code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:11
msgid ""
"The best place to look for examples is the `NumPy issue tracker`_, or the "
"test cases for ``f2py``. Some more use cases are in :ref:`f2py-"
"boilerplating`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:16
msgid "F2PY walkthrough: a basic extension module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:19
msgid "Creating source for a basic extension module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:21
msgid ""
"Consider the following subroutine, contained in a file named :file:`add.f`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:23
msgid ""
"C\n"
"      SUBROUTINE ZADD(A,B,C,N)\n"
"C\n"
"      DOUBLE COMPLEX A(*)\n"
"      DOUBLE COMPLEX B(*)\n"
"      DOUBLE COMPLEX C(*)\n"
"      INTEGER N\n"
"      DO 20 J = 1, N\n"
"         C(J) = A(J)+B(J)\n"
" 20   CONTINUE\n"
"      END\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:26
msgid ""
"This routine simply adds the elements in two contiguous arrays and places "
"the result in a third. The memory for all three arrays must be provided by "
"the calling routine. A very basic interface to this routine can be "
"automatically generated by f2py::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:31
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -m add add.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:33
msgid ""
"This command will produce an extension module named :file:`addmodule.c` in "
"the current directory. This extension module can now be compiled and used "
"from Python just like any other extension module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:38
msgid "Creating a compiled extension module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:40
msgid ""
"You can also get f2py to both compile :file:`add.f` along with the produced "
"extension module leaving only a shared-library extension file that can be "
"imported from Python::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:44 ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:168
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -c -m add add.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:46
msgid ""
"This command produces a Python extension module compatible with your "
"platform. This module may then be imported from Python. It will contain a "
"method for each subroutine in ``add``. The docstring of each method contains "
"information about how the module method may be called:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:51
msgid ""
">>> import add\n"
">>> print(add.zadd.__doc__)\n"
"zadd(a,b,c,n)\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``zadd``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"a : input rank-1 array('D') with bounds (*)\n"
"b : input rank-1 array('D') with bounds (*)\n"
"c : input rank-1 array('D') with bounds (*)\n"
"n : input int"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:67
msgid "Improving the basic interface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:69
msgid ""
"The default interface is a very literal translation of the Fortran code into "
"Python. The Fortran array arguments are converted to NumPy arrays and the "
"integer argument should be mapped to a ``C`` integer. The interface will "
"attempt to convert all arguments to their required types (and shapes) and "
"issue an error if unsuccessful. However, because ``f2py`` knows nothing "
"about the semantics of the arguments (such that ``C`` is an output and ``n`` "
"should really match the array sizes), it is possible to abuse this function "
"in ways that can cause Python to crash. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:78
msgid ">>> add.zadd([1, 2, 3], [1, 2], [3, 4], 1000)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:82
msgid ""
"will cause a program crash on most systems. Under the hood, the lists are "
"being converted to arrays but then the underlying ``add`` function is told "
"to cycle way beyond the borders of the allocated memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:86
msgid ""
"In order to improve the interface, ``f2py`` supports directives. This is "
"accomplished by constructing a signature file. It is usually best to start "
"from the interfaces that ``f2py`` produces in that file, which correspond to "
"the default behavior. To get ``f2py`` to generate the interface file use the "
"``-h`` option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:92
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -h add.pyf -m add add.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:94
msgid ""
"This command creates the ``add.pyf`` file in the current directory. The "
"section of this file corresponding to ``zadd`` is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:97
msgid ""
"subroutine zadd(a,b,c,n) ! in :add:add.f\n"
"   double complex dimension(*) :: a\n"
"   double complex dimension(*) :: b\n"
"   double complex dimension(*) :: c\n"
"   integer :: n\n"
"end subroutine zadd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:100
msgid ""
"By placing intent directives and checking code, the interface can be cleaned "
"up quite a bit so the Python module method is both easier to use and more "
"robust to malformed inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:104
msgid ""
"subroutine zadd(a,b,c,n) ! in :add:add.f\n"
"   double complex dimension(n) :: a\n"
"   double complex dimension(n) :: b\n"
"   double complex intent(out),dimension(n) :: c\n"
"   integer intent(hide),depend(a) :: n=len(a)\n"
"end subroutine zadd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:107
msgid ""
"The intent directive, intent(out) is used to tell f2py that ``c`` is an "
"output variable and should be created by the interface before being passed "
"to the underlying code. The intent(hide) directive tells f2py to not allow "
"the user to specify the variable, ``n``, but instead to get it from the size "
"of ``a``. The depend( ``a`` ) directive is necessary to tell f2py that the "
"value of n depends on the input a (so that it won't try to create the "
"variable n until the variable a is created)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:116
msgid ""
"After modifying ``add.pyf``, the new Python module file can be generated by "
"compiling both ``add.f`` and ``add.pyf``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:119
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -c add.pyf add.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:121
msgid "The new interface's docstring is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:123
msgid ""
">>> import add\n"
">>> print(add.zadd.__doc__)\n"
"c = zadd(a,b)\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``zadd``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"a : input rank-1 array('D') with bounds (n)\n"
"b : input rank-1 array('D') with bounds (n)\n"
"\n"
"Returns\n"
"-------\n"
"c : rank-1 array('D') with bounds (n)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:140
msgid "Now, the function can be called in a much more robust way:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:142
msgid ""
">>> add.zadd([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6])\n"
"array([5.+0.j, 7.+0.j, 9.+0.j])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:147
msgid "Notice the automatic conversion to the correct format that occurred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:150
msgid "Inserting directives in Fortran source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:152
msgid ""
"The robust interface of the previous section can also be generated "
"automatically by placing the variable directives as special comments in the "
"original Fortran code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:158
msgid ""
"For projects where the Fortran code is being actively developed, this may be "
"preferred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:161
msgid "Thus, if the source code is modified to contain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:163
msgid ""
"C\n"
"      SUBROUTINE ZADD(A,B,C,N)\n"
"C\n"
"CF2PY INTENT(OUT) :: C\n"
"CF2PY INTENT(HIDE) :: N\n"
"CF2PY DOUBLE COMPLEX :: A(N)\n"
"CF2PY DOUBLE COMPLEX :: B(N)\n"
"CF2PY DOUBLE COMPLEX :: C(N)\n"
"      DOUBLE COMPLEX A(*)\n"
"      DOUBLE COMPLEX B(*)\n"
"      DOUBLE COMPLEX C(*)\n"
"      INTEGER N\n"
"      DO 20 J = 1, N\n"
"         C(J) = A(J) + B(J)\n"
" 20   CONTINUE\n"
"      END"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:166
msgid "Then, one can compile the extension module using::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:170
msgid ""
"The resulting signature for the function add.zadd is exactly the same one "
"that was created previously. If the original source code had contained "
"``A(N)`` instead of ``A(*)`` and so forth with ``B`` and ``C``, then nearly "
"the same interface can be obtained by placing the ``INTENT(OUT) :: C`` "
"comment line in the source code. The only difference is that ``N`` would be "
"an optional input that would default to the length of ``A``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:179
msgid "A filtering example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:181
msgid ""
"This example shows a function that filters a two-dimensional array of double "
"precision floating-point numbers using a fixed averaging filter. The "
"advantage of using Fortran to index into multi-dimensional arrays should be "
"clear from this example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:186
msgid ""
"C\n"
"      SUBROUTINE DFILTER2D(A,B,M,N)\n"
"C\n"
"      DOUBLE PRECISION A(M,N)\n"
"      DOUBLE PRECISION B(M,N)\n"
"      INTEGER N, M\n"
"CF2PY INTENT(OUT) :: B\n"
"CF2PY INTENT(HIDE) :: N\n"
"CF2PY INTENT(HIDE) :: M\n"
"      DO 20 I = 2,M-1\n"
"         DO 40 J = 2,N-1\n"
"            B(I,J) = A(I,J) +\n"
"     &           (A(I-1,J)+A(I+1,J) +\n"
"     &           A(I,J-1)+A(I,J+1) )*0.5D0 +\n"
"     &           (A(I-1,J-1) + A(I-1,J+1) +\n"
"     &           A(I+1,J-1) + A(I+1,J+1))*0.25D0\n"
" 40      CONTINUE\n"
" 20   CONTINUE\n"
"      END\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:189
msgid ""
"This code can be compiled and linked into an extension module named filter "
"using::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:192
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -c -m filter filter.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:194
msgid ""
"This will produce an extension module in the current directory with a method "
"named ``dfilter2d`` that returns a filtered version of the input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:199
msgid "``depends`` keyword example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:201
msgid "Consider the following code, saved in the file ``myroutine.f90``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:203
msgid ""
"subroutine s(n, m, c, x)\n"
"\timplicit none\n"
"  \tinteger, intent(in) :: n, m\n"
"  \treal(kind=8), intent(out), dimension(n,m) :: x\n"
"  \treal(kind=8), intent(in) :: c(:)\n"
"\n"
"\tx = 0.0d0\n"
"\tx(1, 1) = c(1)\n"
"\n"
"end subroutine s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:206
msgid ""
"Wrapping this with ``python -m numpy.f2py -c myroutine.f90 -m myroutine``, "
"we can do the following in Python::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:209
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> import myroutine\n"
">>> x = myroutine.s(2, 3, np.array([5, 6, 7]))\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([[5., 0., 0.],\n"
"   [0., 0., 0.]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:216
msgid ""
"Now, instead of generating the extension module directly, we will create a "
"signature file for this subroutine first. This is a common pattern for multi-"
"step extension module generation. In this case, after running"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:220
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py myroutine.f90 -m myroutine -h myroutine.pyf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:224
msgid "the following signature file is generated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:226
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"! Note: the context of this file is case sensitive.\n"
"\n"
"python module myroutine ! in \n"
"    interface  ! in :myroutine\n"
"        subroutine s(n,m,c,x) ! in :myroutine:myroutine.f90\n"
"            integer intent(in) :: n\n"
"            integer intent(in) :: m\n"
"            real(kind=8) dimension(:),intent(in) :: c\n"
"            real(kind=8) dimension(n,m),intent(out),depend(m,n) :: x\n"
"        end subroutine s\n"
"    end interface \n"
"end python module myroutine\n"
"\n"
"! This file was auto-generated with f2py (version:1.23.0.dev0+120."
"g4da01f42d).\n"
"! See:\n"
"! https://web.archive.org/web/20140822061353/http://cens.ioc.ee/projects/"
"f2py2e"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:229
msgid ""
"Now, if we run ``python -m numpy.f2py -c myroutine.pyf myroutine.f90`` we "
"see an error; note that the signature file included a ``depend(m,n)`` "
"statement for ``x`` which is not necessary. Indeed, editing the file above "
"to read"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:233
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"! Note: the context of this file is case sensitive.\n"
"\n"
"python module myroutine ! in \n"
"    interface  ! in :myroutine\n"
"        subroutine s(n,m,c,x) ! in :myroutine:myroutine.f90\n"
"            integer intent(in) :: n\n"
"            integer intent(in) :: m\n"
"            real(kind=8) dimension(:),intent(in) :: c\n"
"            real(kind=8) dimension(n,m),intent(out) :: x\n"
"        end subroutine s\n"
"    end interface \n"
"end python module myroutine\n"
"\n"
"! This file was auto-generated with f2py (version:1.23.0.dev0+120."
"g4da01f42d).\n"
"! See:\n"
"! https://web.archive.org/web/20140822061353/http://cens.ioc.ee/projects/"
"f2py2e"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py-examples.rst:236
msgid ""
"and running ``f2py -c myroutine.pyf myroutine.f90`` yields correct results."
msgstr ""

